Package: hotR
Title: Structured Threshold Model for Heat-Onset Risk Estimation
Version: 0.1.0
Authors@R: 
    person(
      given  = "Monica",
      family = "Robles Fontan",
      email  = "mroblesfontan@g.harvard.edu",
      role   = c("aut", "cre"),
      comment = c(ORCID = "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5337-8280")
    )
Description: Implements the structured threshold model (STM) for estimating
    the heat-onset risk threshold (HOT) from daily mortality time series.
    The HOT is the temperature above which heat-attributable mortality begins
    to rise. The model links daily death counts to temperature exposure
    via a smooth hinge function, adjusts for long-term trend and seasonality
    using a natural spline basis, and accounts for overdispersion via a
    negative binomial likelihood. Parameters are estimated by block coordinate
    descent. Both Wald and sandwich covariance estimators are provided for
    inference on the HOT. The method is designed for short and noisy mortality
    series where temperature exposure is concentrated in warm regions.
